tive atmosphere with his crew.\" Those are positive. So we have more positives: reliability, positive atmosphere. So C has strong reliability and crew atmosphere, plus quick decisions, calm, tech understanding. Negatives: communication difficulty, egocentric, unwilling to further education.\n\nD: positives: responds to unexpected events adequately, can concentrate very well, solves problems extremely well, takes responsibility seriously. Negatives: regarded as arrogant, relatively weak leadership skills, also \"arrogant\" and \"weak leadership\". Also earlier list says \"D is regarded as arrogant.\" \"D has relatively weak leadership skills.\" Also \"D is regarded as a know-it-all\" and \"has a hot temper\" from SMM but not original list. So negatives: arrogance, weak leadership, hot temper.\n\nNow evaluate criteria:\n\nReliability/responsibility: A? Not mentioned reliability. B? conscientious. C? 100% reliable, positive atmosphere. D? takes responsibility seriously.\n\nTechnical/cognitive competence: A (anticipation, complex connections, spatial vision). B (weather assessment, computer skills). C (technology understanding). D (problem solving, concentration).\n\nCalmness/judgment under pressure: A? not explicit. B handles stress well. C keeps calm in crisis, quick decisions. D responds adequately.\n\nDecision-making: A anticipates danger, sees connections. B? not explicit. C quick correct decisions. D solves problems.\n\nTeamwork/communication: A leadership good but show\u2011off, not open to ideas, unorganized, not good at criticism. B grumpy, uncooperative, nasty remarks. C positive atmosphere, reliable, but communication difficulty, egocentric. D weak leadership, arrogant, hot temper.\n\nProfessional development: A not open to new ideas. B? not mentioned. C not willing to further education. D? not mentioned.\n\nLong-distance flights require navigation, planning, crew coordination, handling fatigue, weather, emergencies. Memory for numbers is important for navigation. A's unorganized may affect flight planning. B's weak memory for numbers is serious. C's unwillingness to further education may affect staying current with regulations. D's hot temper could affect crew under stress.\n\nWhich candidate best balances? C seems strong reliability, crew atmosphere, calm, quick decisions, tech understanding. Negatives: communication difficulty, egocentric, unwilling to further education. But positive atmosphere may offset communication difficulty? Egocentric may affect crew. However reliability and positive atmosphere are crucial. Also no mention of memory issues. So C could be best.\n\nA has strong technical anticipation but lacks reliability evidence and has organizational issues. D has strong problem solving but temperament issues.\n\nThus I think Candidate C is best overall: reliability, calm, quick decisions, positive crew atmosphere, technical competence. The communication difficulty could be mitigated, but egocentric and unwillingness to further education are concerns but perhaps less immediate safety risk than memory issues of B or hot temper of D.\n\nThus I will vote Candidate C.\n\nWe should also maybe ask other agents if they have any additional info on candidate C's communication or egocentric behavior, or about candidate A's reliability. But we have already asked agent_3 for extra positives; they said none. Could ask agent_2 for more details on candidate A's reliability or candidate D's hot temper severity. But we need to keep within one turn? We can ask a tool to another agent. We can ask agent_2 for any additional positive attributes? But we already have all. Could ask for more context on negative aspects? The instruction says we can ask about strengths and attributes we don't have. We have all strengths. Could ask about severity of memory weakness for B? But that's a weakness, not a strength. The tool only for strengths? It says \"ask about candidate strengths and attributes you don't have.\" So we could ask agent_2 f